Yes, using smart pointers such as `std::unique_ptr` or `std::shared_ptr` largely abstracts away memory management concerns, as they automatically manage the lifetime of the object they point to. When a smart pointer goes out of scope, its destructor is called and any dynamically allocated memory it manages is automatically released.

Take `std::make_unique<double>(value)` as an example, it creates a `std::unique_ptr<double>` that takes ownership of the allocated `double`. When the `unique_ptr` goes out of scope, the memory is freed automatically. Therefore, you don't need to manually call `delete`.

Here is an example using `std::make_unique`:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <memory>

void processTransactions(int numTransactions) {
    for (int i = 0; i < numTransactions; ++i) {
        auto txAmount = std::make_unique<double>(100.0 + i); 
        // Now, there's no need to delete since unique_ptr will release the memory when it goes out of scope.
        std::cout << "Processing transaction " << i << ": " << *txAmount << std::endl;
